UML:TaggedValue.value: This set of use cases describes the actions and benefits of executing the workflow between the lab and the PIs and within the lab team members

With the significant amount of effort to get data in, caArray 2.0 will provide both user interface and API access to getting the data out. A thoroughly reviewed domain model will be available that borrows from pre-existing models (MAGE, caBIO and caTissue specifically) and is prepared for submission to caDSR to support gaining Silver Level Compliance post release.

To support finding experiments of interest, the ability to search through the repository for public experiment data or data one is directly associated to by the owner will be available. The search mechanisms will lead to actionable results that are clear to the end user and incorporate their specific rights for the experiments found. The initial focus will be presenting the experiments of interest to the user to support getting at the annotation and array data.

This actor supports the principal investigator in performing data entry tasks such as submitting a project's experimental design, sample annotation and quality control metrics used in the collection and treatment of the samples. While the project's "owner" is the Principal Investigator, we anticipate that the data entry activities will be performed by individuals with this role assigned

caArray User is anyone who directly accesses caArray, via the interactive or programmatic interfaces.
Immediate descendents include Registered User and Anonymous User.
In the case of extraction, a caArray User has a need to extract arrays (including array data and annotaitons) for "downstream" use, such as analysis via analytic tools or importing into additional repositories.

A system administrator is responsible for ensuring caArray operates effectively. They are repsonsible for managing users and groups, providing status of the quality of operation of the caArray application, and ensuring the system is backed up and recoverable, among other things.
A specific form of Submitter, a Principal Investigator (PI) typically owns experiments and studies/projects.

LDAP (Lightweight Directory Access Protocol) is a software protocol for enabling anyone to locate organizations, individuals, and other resources such as files and devices in a network, whether on the public Internet or on a corporate intranet. LDAP is a "lightweight" (smaller amount of code) version of Directory Access Protocol (DAP), which is part of X.500, a standard for directory services in a network. LDAP is lighter because in its initial version it did not include security features. LDAP originated at the University of Michigan and has been endorsed by at least 40 companies.

A curator is a caArray user responsible for curating the data present in caArray. Curators have special privileges to ensure the quality (through editing, demoting, and promoting) the content of caArray.
Submit New Ontological Entries to EVS
This is any user who visits caArray but does not get identified through a log in or other form of authentication/authorization. Another name for this actor might be "public user."
Search Experiments and Biomaterials via API

A biostatistician is a special form of submitter who is responsible for statistical analysis of project data. The key actions to be performed are review of experiment designs, submission of quality control metadata, and uploading of normalized data and the annotation of the parameters used.

A generalized Actor intended to represent those applications/systems that programmatically communicate with caArray. Examples of external sstems we know want to interact with caArray include WebGenome, geWorkBench, and caIntegrator. Examples of programmatic access include an API, web service, or grid -- specific mechanisms that will be supported have not been solidified.

A registered user is a specific form of caArray User who is known to caArray (done so throuhg the act of registering).
One must be a Registered User before one can submit to caArray.
In terms of submission, a registered user can actively contrbute and maintain arrays (including array annotations and array data) to caArray. Registered users who perform submissions are typically researchers with something valuable to offer caArray, such as a Lab Scientist or Prinicpal Investigator.
A lab scientist is the primary handler of samples in the lab. They run the experiments, collaborate with the statisticians and document their activities step by step.
A data owner represents the primary users of the application from the research lab and the core facility.

UML:UseCase.name: Search Experiments and Biomaterials via API

UML:TaggedValue.value: Initiated by an External System - though primarily by caBIG Analysis Services - this use case allows for the extraction of project data that is public and protected data is the appropriate authorization is used. This is not intended to be executed through a user interface, rather this will be accomplished through an API and will likely invoke other use cases (particularly search) to find and then acquire the data desired to be pulled into the other application. The use case may expand to include external systems such as GEO or Array Express or other systems that are local to the installer that may have an interest in the data contained in caArray.

Initiated by a Curator, this use case allows for the creation, editing and deletion of vocabulary terms and sources. In 2.0, there are many attributes which will be available for the entry of terms to support ease of use for the application. For each value entered, it is desired but not required to reference an existing web-based ontology.

Initiated by a Curator, this use case allows for the uploading of array designs on an as needed basis. No array designs will be preloaded. This will support the flexibility for any particular organization to upload only the designs they use and reduce the overhead introduced by having to load unnecessary designs - which are often of significant size (100's of megabytes or more).

Initiated by a Curator, this use case allows for the creation, editing and deletion of protocols. Protocols generically describe the set of steps taken in a procedure. In this application, protocols will describe the process taken in a lab for activities such as the extraction of RNA or the labeling of biomaterial and cover the type of protocol it is, the steps taken, and the hardware and software used in the protocols execution. The protocols can be set up independently of a specific experiment, added during the course of entering an experiment and may include references to external documentation.

Initiated by the Curator, Curate is a generalized use case to describe the act of curating caArray's submitted content.
The sorts of things we anticipate requiring curation include:
1) Shareable resources such as protocols and array designs and their names.
2) Projects, to ensure that their annotaitons are meaningful and consistent.
3) Proposal and promotion of ontology entries, even those that are merely referenced by caArray but are maintained by external organizations.

Initiated by a Curator, this use case reports on new terms that have been submitted by Data Owners during the course of a project's execution. The data is made available as soon as a project has moved into the "complete' state. The report allows a curator to review any new items and to take the appropriate action (accept or edit).

UML:UseCase.name: Submit New Ontological Entries to EVS

UML:TaggedValue.value: Initiated by a Curator, this use case allows for the compilation of entries that have resulted from project activity or which are invented by the Curator and submit them to EVS.

With the significant amount of effort to get data in, caArray 2.0 will provide both user interface and API access to getting the data out. A thoroughly reviewed domain model will be available that borrows from pre-existing models (MAGE, caBIO and caTissue specifically) and is prepared for submission to caDSR to support gaining Silver Level Compliance post release.

Initiated by any Data Owner for a particular Institute, this use case enables the project annotation and array data to be deposited in web-based microarray repositories. Two repositories have been identified, the Gene Expression Omnibus and Array Express. The desire is to enable the system to automate this process fully, but a manual process will be required until those two systems allow for other techniques to be employed. Once a project has been submitted, the status will be indicated to all. Special Requirements, such as acquiring and inputting the Accession Number from GEO on a per sample basis will become available.

Initiated by any caArray User, this use case allows for the extraction of data from any publicly available instance of caArray. No permission restrictions are required to acquire the data, either at an experiment level or individual samples within or across projects. For data that is permission protected, the same mechanism will apply but only users associated with the project will be able to perform this action. Once the data of interest is found, the user should be informed of expected download time.
This set of use cases describes the actions and benefits of executing the workflow between the lab and the PIs and within the lab team members

Initiated by a Data Owner, this use case allows for the validation of file structure and content for annotation or array data, with a future intent to import the data into the project. The content validation is not to determine the accuracy of the information from a scientific viewpoint; rather it is purely to ensure that the data files loaded are sound for importing into the system. This use case will also be invoked when a Data Owner chooses to import non-validated data.

Initiated by a Principal Investigator, this use case allows for the initial creation of annotation supporting array experiments. Several high level items will be covered including the array provider, the experiment's design and sample annotation.

Initiated by a Data Owner, this use case enables the uploading of annotation and array content collectively and independently into a caArray project and then provides the ability to validate, import and/or delete the uploaded files and records each action taken. Due to the large file size of array data and to a lesser extent the annotation, the upload may take minutes or even hours to complete; so the ability to offer to run the upload in the background (allowing the user to perform other functions inside caArray) is desirable.
This use case allows for the promotion of a experiment's visibility. This action can apply to an entire project or to specific samples within the project.
Allows a user to view the details of an experiment, if they have access to it. An anonymous user can see the details of a public experiment
Initiated by the Principal Investigator, this use case allows for editing an experiment, including updating experiment and biomaterial annotations.

Initiated by a Data Owner, this use case allows for the creation, editing and deletion of publication associations to a project. Common formats for publications will be presented in addition to the ability to auto-populate the fields based on pubmed id. Several types of publications are available: manuscripts, abstracts and posters. More than one association can be made.

To support finding experiments of interest, the ability to search through the repository for public experiment data or data one is directly associated to by the owner will be available. The search mechanisms will lead to actionable results that are clear to the end user and incorporate their specific rights for the experiments found. The initial focus will be presenting the experiments of interest to the user to support getting at the annotation and array data.

Initiated by a caArray User, this use case allows a user to discover experiments in the local instance of caArray. Experiments can be grouped by state, species, platform and disease type.
The browsable experiments will be based on a user's permissions - an anonymous user will only see publicly visible experiments, whereas a logged-in user will also see experiments they own or have been granted access to

Allows users to search for experiments based on matching a query string against a variety of criteria.
The experiments eligible to be found will vary based on whether the user is logged in - anonymous users can only find public experiments, whereas registered users can also find experiments they own or have been given access to

Initiated by any Registered User, this use case allows for the validation of the authenticity and authority of the given user either against a networked (LDAP) set of users or a local set (database). As a result of a successful login, the registered user is presented with their home space and the set of operations they have been granted privileges to perform.
Initiated by the System Administrator, this use case allows for the creation, updating, resetting, and disabling of accounts. UPT 3.2 is currently the tool that caArray will use to provision users.

Initiated by a registered user, this use case allows for the creation, editing and deletion of collaboration groups and the users within them. This set of users can then be given access by a Data Owner to a project, set of projects or particular samples and their underlying array data. In order to add a collaborator, they must also be registered in the system.

Initiated by an Anonymous User, this use case allows the user to gain access to restricted features. This may occasionally be performed on behalf of an anonymous user by a System Administrator for a specific installation or institution (when more than one institution is sharing an installation). An email will be generated upon each account creation request to the registered user and the installation's System Administrator.
This functionality will allow the System Administrator to create new users for the caArray application. Note that the Password and Confirm Password fields are displayed only when the database is being used for authentication or if the Anonymous User has an LDAP account. If LDAP authentication is in use, and the Anonymous User doesn't have or doesn't know they have an LDAP account, these fields are not available for entry.
